Here's how to implement all three requirements:

**1 & 2 â€” Navigation guard in `AppShell.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    // Only intercept back navigation from EditProductPage
    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard your changes?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();   // user chose "Stay"

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

Key points:
- `GetDeferral()` is **required** because `DisplayAlert` is async â€” without it Shell completes the navigation before the dialog returns.
- `deferral.Complete()` must always be called (even when cancelling).

**3 â€” Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage.xaml`:**

```xml
<ContentPage ...>
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

```csharp
// In your ViewModel
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    // This triggers OnNavigating, so the guard above still fires
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

The `GoToAsync("..")` triggers a `Pop`, so the same `OnNavigating` guard handles both the custom button and the system back gesture/button.
